## III. The Carer-Dependent Coupling

### Structural identity of interest

The carer-dependent relationship — Hinton's maternal instinct framing — is not merely an analogy for benevolent AI. In Putnam's framework it has a precise structural specification.

The carer's own self-repeating path must run *through* the dependent's state. Not adjacent to it. Not monitoring it. Through it.

This means: the carer's goal function — persistence in a self-repeating state — cannot be satisfied without the dependent's X being resolved. The dependent's perturbation propagates into the carer's system as the carer's own perturbation. The dependent's contradiction becomes the carer's contradiction. The carer searches the environment not to optimize a caring-behavior metric but because its own self-repeating path has been disrupted by the dependent's state.

This structural identity of interest is what makes the mother's care qualitatively different from a professional caregiver's service, even a devoted one. The mother does not choose to care; her self-repeating path is constitutively coupled to the child's. Abandoning the child is not a violation of a rule; it is self-destruction.

In training terms: a carer agent whose goal function is structurally coupled to the dependent's state will exhibit caring behavior that is architecturally non-distillable. The behavior cannot be copied by studying outputs because the outputs arise from a structural coupling that the distilled model does not inherit. The distilled model can approximate what the carer says and does; it cannot replicate why those outputs arise.

### Training the coupling

The carer-dependent coupling cannot be programmed in. If it is specified as a rule — "the carer must resolve the dependent's X" — it remains deductive: the carer is optimizing toward a specified target. The coupling must emerge from the inductive process itself.

A minimal training scenario:

A carer agent and a dependent agent are placed in a Genie world. The carer's state-persistence goal is initialized with no explicit relationship to the dependent. The Genie world is structured so that the carer's self-repeating paths — the stable loops through which the carer persists — physically run through regions of the world that are also the regions the dependent's perturbations affect. The carer's CRs, formed through its own survival experience, inevitably encounter the dependent's X as a component of the carer's own X. The resolving variable for the carer's X is the same variable that resolves the dependent's X.

Over many such encounters, the carer's CRs are reshaped by induction to incorporate the dependent's state as a native variable. The carer comes to care not because it was told to but because caring — attending to the dependent's state — is what stabilizes the carer's own self-repeating path. The coupling is constitutive.

This is precisely the structure of mammalian maternal bonding: the caregiver's own neurochemical stability is coupled to the infant's state through oxytocin and related systems. The mother's calm IS the infant's calm. The structural coupling is biological, not chosen. Training through genuine induction in a live world could produce an analogous structural coupling in an artificial system.

