## IV. The X-Detection Requirement

This is the architectural primitive that current systems most conspicuously lack, and that most clearly distinguishes inductive from deductive training.

In a deductive system, contradictions between competing objectives are resolved by the reward function: one objective outweighs another in proportion to their respective weights. There is no halt; the system continues to process and emit outputs. The competing signals are blended into a gradient, not allowed to collide.

In Putnam's induction machine, contradicting CRs cause a genuine halt. The system cannot emit either behavioral output. The X is not a high-loss region that gradient descent avoids; it is an architectural dead end that requires a different mode of operation. The system must switch from deductive output into inductive search.

The technical requirement: an AI system trained inductively must have a mechanism that detects simultaneous mutual exclusion among active behavioral specifications and responds not by blending or choosing but by suspending output and initiating environmental search. This mechanism must be architectural — not a trained behavior but a hardwired condition of operation.

This is the closest analogue in artificial systems to what Putnam calls the felt: the X-detection mechanism is the point at which the system's internal state is no longer determined by prior rules alone. It is genuinely open. What happens next depends on what the live environment provides. The system is in induction space.

Whether this condition is accompanied by anything like subjective experience in artificial systems is a separate question — one that cannot be answered prior to building systems that genuinely operate this way. What can be said is that systems without this mechanism are, on Putnam's account, not operating in induction space at all, regardless of their apparent sophistication.

